Describe the structure of the data. Number of records and fields in each record?¶

  • The data has 786363 records and 29 fields in each record.

  • We have 4 numerical features, 4 date variables, and 21 categorical variables (including 3 boolean variables).

    Categorical Variables:

    • Target Variable: isFraud
    • Unique Identifier for customers: accountNumber, customerId,
    • Merchant Info: merchantName, merchantCity, merchantState, merchantZip, merchantCountryCode, merchantCategoryCode
    • Card Info: cardCVV, enteredCVV, cardLast4Digits, cardPresent
    • Pos Info: posEntryMode, posConditionCode, posOnPremises
    • Transaction Info: transactionType
    • Others: acqCountry, echoBuffer, recurringAuthInd, expirationDateKeyInMatch

    Numerical Variables: creditLimit, availableMoney, transactionAmount, currentBalance

    Date Variables: transactionDateTime, currentExpDate, accountOpenDate, dateOfLastAddressChange

Generate some basic summary statistics for each field.¶

By checking the missing values for each columns, we can see that 6 columns (echoBuffer, recurringAuthInd, posOnPremises, merchantCity, merchantState, and merchantZip) from our dataset are 100% missing. I would like to drop them since they are not able to provide any value to our analysis and model.

Besides, I would also want to drop either accountNumber or customerId because they are identical. I choose to drop accountNumber here.

Lastly, there are another 5 columns (acqCountry, posEntryMode, merchantCountryCode, transactionType, posConditionCode) with 0.05% - 0.5% missing. Some imputations are probably needed. As they are all categorical variables, I would like to fill in "Missing" for missing values to keep the original distribution of the data and avoid any bias.

Some hypotheses about the data structure...¶

  • The histogram above aligns with our assumption above that the distribution of numerical variables is right-skewed.
  • Most of transactions fall in the range of \$0 to \\$500. 53.88% is less than $100, and 10.75% of the transaction amount is only less than \\$10.
  • Based on the histogram by isFraud, we can see that the trend is different between fraud and non-fraud transactions.
    • The distribution of non-fraud transactions is more skewed to the right than the distribution of fraud transaction, which means that fraud transactions tend to involve more money.
    • Looking at the summary stats, the average amount for fraud transactions is \$225 while the average non-fraud transaction amount is \\$135.
    • 50% of non-fraud transactions has amount less than \$87 while only 25% of fraud transactions has amount less than \\$87.
    • Although the non-fraud transactions are mostly small amount, the maximum transaction amount for non-fraud transactions (\$2011) is much higher than the maximum transaction amount for fraud transactions (\\$1608).

Thus, according to the analysis above, we can make the hypothese that fraudsters tend to make transactions with small to medium amount. It is less likely to be a very small amount because it is not attractive enough for fraudsters to take the risk. It is also less likely to be a very big amount because it would then be too noticable and risky. Note that the fraud transaction is only 1.58% of all transactions. It is possible that it is not representative enough. We might want more records to valid our analysis here. We will discuss this in the last section of this report.

Part 3: Data Wrangling - Duplicate Transactions¶

I noticed a number of what look like duplicated transactions in the data set. One type of duplicated transaction is a reversed transaction, where a purchase is followed by a reversal. Another example is a multi-swipe, where a vendor accidentally charges a customer's card multiple times within a short time span. Here are some questions I tried to answer:

• Can we programmatically identify reversed and multi-swipe transactions?

• What total number of transactions and total dollar amount do we estimate for the reversed transactions? For the multi-swipe transactions? (consider the first transaction to be "normal" and exclude it from the number of transaction and dollar amount counts)

• Did we find anything interesting about either kind of transaction?

Reversed Transactions¶

If we filter the data by transactionType == 'REVERSAL', we would get 20,303 reversal transactions, and the total amount is \$2,821,792.5.

Ideally, each reversal transaction should be able to match with a normal purchase transaction based on the following criteria:

  • The reversal transaction and the matched purchase transaction have the same customerId, transactionAmount, merchantName, and cardLast4Digits.
  • The reversal transaction happens later than the matched purchase transaction.

With the 2 criteria, I tried to match a normal purchase transaction with each reversal transaction:

  • Step 1: Create 2 seperate datasets purchase and reversal from the original dataset, one containing all purchasing records and the other containing all reversal records.
  • Step 2: Left join the 2 data set (left: reversal, right: purchase) by customerId, transactionAmount, merchantName, and cardLast4Digits. Basically, I was trying to find a matched purchase transaction for each reversal transaction.
  • Step 3: Filter for matched transactions which the purchase transaction time is earlier than the reversal transaction time

  • Step 4: Both purchase and reversal data have some duplicates and will over-estimate the result if joining together (e.g. There will be multiple purchase transactions with the same amount if it is recurring). Thus, we split the data from step 3 into two parts.

    • One includes the matched transactions of which both reversal and purchase transactions are only used once. This part is considered done and these transactions will be removed from the original purchase and reversal data sets for the following steps.
    • Another part contains matched transactions of which either reversal or purchase transactions are used more than once. We still need to find a matched purchase transaction for the rest of reversal transactions.

  • Step 5: Use a for loop scan to find the latest purchase transactions that fulfills the two criterias mentioned above for each reversal transaction.

  • Step 6: Combine the result from step 5 and the first part of data from step 4 to get the final results.

We can see that for all 20,303 reversal transactions with total amount as \$2,821,792.5.

  • I am able to match the normal purchase transactions to 17,756 reversal transactions with total amount as \$2,666,167.82.
  • I am not able to match the normal purchase transactions to the rest of 2,547 reversal transactions with total amount as \$155,624.68.

The possible reasons for the 2,547 reversal transactions that can't be matched are:

  1. Data Quality: Some Transaction Data is missing from the available data set.
  2. Different Transaction Amount: The transaction amount is different in the purchase and reversal transactions.

Multi-Swipe Transactions¶

Based on the description above, multi-swipe transactios should meet the following criteria:

  • They are purchase transactions.
  • They have the same customerId, transactionAmount, merchantName, and cardLast4Digits.
  • The time duration between one swipe to another swipe should be less than 5 minutes.

With the 2 criteria, I follow these steps to identify multi-swipe transactions:

  • Step 1: Select duplicated rows based on customerId, transactionAmount, merchantName, and cardLast4Digits from the purchase data set created in the last section to find transactions of same amount within the same account/card from the same merchant, which is eligible to be multi-swipe transactions
  • Step 2: Calculate the time difference between the transaction time of each row and transaction time of each row - 1
  • Step 3: Select rows which time difference is less than 5 minutes as multi-swipe transactions
  • Step 4: Create multiple features for multi-swipe transactions to further analysis
    • Multi: 1 for multi-swipe transaction excluding the first 'normal' transaction, 0 for others
    • Multi_All: 1 for first 'normal' transaction of multi-swipe transactions, 0 for others
    • Multi_T: 0 for non multi-swipe transactions, > 0 for all multi-swipe transactions including the first 'normal' transaction. The number is the rank number for all multi-swipe transactions for a certain customer based on transaction time. All transactions for the same multi-swipe behavior will get the same number.

We can see that for all 65,512 purchase transactions with total amount as \$3,657,387.75.

  • 7,449 purchase transactions with total amount as \$1,102,920.99.
  • The remaining 58,063 purchase transactions with total amount as \$2,554,466.76 are not multi-swipe transactions.

The fraud rate for multi-swipe transactions (1.7%) is much higher than the other group (0.3%). This label could probably provide some insights for our model.

Part 4: ML Model¶

Fraud is a problem for any bank. Fraud can take many forms, whether it is someone stealing a single credit card, to large batches of stolen credit card numbers being used on the web, or even a mass compromise of credit card numbers stolen from a merchant via tools like credit card skimming devices.

Each of the transactions in the dataset has a field called isFraud. We want to build a predictive model to determine whether a given transaction will be fraudulent or not.

Data Cleansing¶

Based on the value count distribution, we can see that each one of the 5 variables has a major category that over 40% of the records fall into. Thus, I used the mode value to impute for missing values in these columns.

matchCVV¶

CVV (Card verification value) is a three- or four-digit number on the card that adds an extra layer of security for the credit card. If the CVV is entered incorrectly when making transactions, it is more likely that the transaction is fraud.

The original data set haves 2 columns related to CVV: cardCVV and enteredCVV. I created a new feature named matchCVV to check whether the CVV is entered correctly for each transaction.

  • matchCVV: 1 if cardCVV = enteredCVV, otherwise 0
In [54]:
df_new['matchCVV'] = (df_new['cardCVV'] == df_new['enteredCVV']).astype(int)
df_new = df_new.drop(['cardCVV', 'enteredCVV'], axis=1)

matchCountry¶

In most cases, the transaction should be made in the same country as the country that the customer acquired the card. It is more likely to be a fraudulent case if the transaction is made in another country.

The original data set haves 2 columns: acqCountry and merchantCountryCode. I created a new feature named matchCountry to check whether the acqCountry matches with the merchantCountryCode.

  • matchCountry: 1 if acqCountry = merchantCountryCode, otherwise 0
In [55]:
df_new['matchCountry'] = (df_new['acqCountry'] == df_new['merchantCountryCode']).astype(int)
df_new = df_new.drop(['acqCountry', 'merchantCountryCode'], axis=1)

newMerchant¶

The merchantName column has too many unique values. If we do one-hot encoding on it, we may face the issue of curse of dimentionality. To solve this, I converted it to a new feature named newMerchant to identify whether the transaction is the first time that the customer has interacted with the merchant. If the transaction is made in a merchant that the customer has never shopped with, it has higher possibility that the transaction is a fraud.

  • newMerchant: 1 if the transaction is the first time that the customer has interacted with the merchant, otherwise 0

We can further improve this feature if we are able to get more historical transaction data. The data we have now is limited since it is only for year 2016.

SMOTE (Balance the Data)¶

In the original dataset, the class within the dependent variable isFraud is pretty imbalanced. Fraud cases are much less than non-fraud ones. In order to balance the dataset and improve model performance, I used the SMOTE() function to oversample the data.

SMOTE() function generates synthetic samples for the minority class by randomly selecting one or more of the k-nearest neighbors for each example in the minority class. Before this oversampling process, we have 1.58% fraud the data is reconstructed and balanced.

Modeling¶

Define Evaluation Metrics¶

We need to be careful about the model evalutaion metrics as we are dealing with imbalanced data. Prioritizing precision or recall is important in such cases and must be evaluated based on use case. Below are the metrics I have designed in the model evaluation function:

  • Accuracy is the most common performance metric used for classification algorithms. Accuracy is mainly used for a balanced dataset. It is defined as the ratio of the number of correct predictions made to all the predictions made. Note that it may not work well with unbalanced datasets as it may get biased towards the majority class.

  • ROC-AUC is a typical evaluation metric for model performance. However, it can sometimes be misleading in some very imbalanced applications (just as our case). A ROC curve can still look pretty good (ie better than random) while misclassifying most or all of the minority class.

  • Precision is an importance evaluation metric. It indicates that from all the points predicted to positive how many of them are actually positive.

  • Recall is also an influential evaluation metric. Under the same model performance, recall could suggest how much percentage of real frauds have our models captured, which also tightly connect to our business goal. It supports finding the optimal threshold.

  • PR-Curve could help to find a balanced point of the threshold between recall and precision, where marginal increase of recall shows down in PR-curve. It is specifically tailored for the detection of rare events and are pretty useful in those scenarios. They will show that your classifier has a low performance if it is misclassifying most or all of the minority class.

  • F1 Score, which is the harmonic mean of precision and recall, can give us a more comprehensive understanding of the model.

If we have more time, we could also consider dividing data into multiple deciles and ploting the Lift Chart to further evaluate model performance.

Reference: The Relationship Between Precision-Recall and ROC Curves

    fpr_1, tpr_1, thresholds_1 = roc_curve(y_test, probas_1)
    roc_auc_0 = auc(fpr_0, tpr_0)
    roc_auc_1 = auc(fpr_1, tpr_1)
    print("Area under the ROC curve - train: %f" % roc_auc_0)
    print("Area under the ROC curve - test: %f" % roc_auc_1)
    # Plot ROC curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    plt.plot(fpr_0, tpr_0, label='ROC curve - train(AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_0, color='r')
    plt.plot(fpr_1, tpr_1, label='ROC curve - test (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_1, color='b')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
In [93]:
def model_eval(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, threshold=0.5):
    y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    # The first column is the probability of the predicted output being zero, that is 1 - 𝑝(𝑥). 
    # The second column is the probability that the output is one, or 𝑝(𝑥).
    #y_pred_default = model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred = (y_prob >= threshold).astype('bool')
    
    print("Accuracy:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("Precision:", metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("Recall:", metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("F1 Score:", metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred))
    
    print('*********************************************************************************')
    #confusion_matrix
    cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    print("Confusion Matrix:")
    print(cnf_matrix)
    
    print('*********************************************************************************')
    #roc_curve
    roc_plot(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

The most outstanding advantage for XGBoost model is that it tends to avoid overfitting. As we saw a pretty high AUC on training set earlier, I think XGBoost model is surely going to provide us better prediction here.

Hyperparameter Tuning (Bayesian Optimization)¶

In order to further improve the XGBoost model performance, we used the bayesian optimization for hyperparameter tuning.

The reason why we chose Bayesian optimization methods instead of grid search and random search is that Bayesian optimization methods are more efficient. With Bayesian optimization, hyperparameters are selected in an informed manner. It would prioritize hyperparameters that appear to be more promising from past results and find the best hyperparameters in fewer iterations and shorter period of time than both grid search and random search.

Reference: XGBoost and Random Forest with Bayesian Optimisation

In [84]:
#Bayesian optimization
def bayesian_optimization(dataset, function, parameters):
   X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test = dataset
   n_iterations = 5
   gp_params = {"alpha": 1e-4}

   BO = BayesianOptimization(function, parameters)
   BO.maximize(n_iter=n_iterations, **gp_params)

   return BO, BO.max
In [85]:
def xgb_optimization(cv_splits, eval_set):
    def function(eta, max_depth, min_child_weight, colsample_bytree, subsample, gamma):
            return cross_val_score(
                   XGBClassifier(
                   objective="binary:logistic",
                   learning_rate=max(eta, 0),
                   max_depth=int(max_depth),
                   subsample=max(subsample, 0),
                   colsample_bytree=max(colsample_bytree, 0),
                   scale_pos_weight = len(y_train[y_train == 0])/
                                      len(y_train[y_train == 1]),  
                   seed=101,
                   gamma=max(gamma, 0),
                   lambda=10,
                   min_child_weight=int(min_child_weight)),
                   X=X_train, 
                   y=y_train, 
                   cv=cv_splits,
                   scoring="f1",
                   fit_params={
                        "early_stopping_rounds": 10, 
                        "eval_metric": "logloss", 
                        "eval_set": [(X_test, y_test)]},
                   n_jobs=-1).mean()

    parameters = {'eta': (0.01, 0.4),
                  'max_depth': (3, 6),
                  'min_child_weight': (10, 30),
                  'colsample_bytree': (0.2, 0.8),
                  'subsample': (0.5, 1),
                  'gamma': (0, 2)}
    
    
    return function, parameters

Feature Importance¶

We finally settled down on the model. Now we want to take a look at the feature importance plot to identify important features and come up with busines strategies.

The top 10 important features include:

  • cardPresent: This is a boolean variable showing whether the card is presented when making the transaction. We should be more confident about the transaction if the physical card is showing up along with the customer himself/herself.
  • posEntryMode (05, 09) and posConditionCode (08): The pos entry code and condition code can be related to fraud cases. We should work with other team members to figure out what those code stand for, and then try to come up with some useful insights.
  • newMerchant: It is a newly generated feature and it indicates whether the transaction is happening with a brand new merchant that the customer have never shopped with. We should be very careful about those unusual transactions. We can also think about setting up special alarm system for those transactions.
  • transaction_Amount: We have visualizations above to show that the distributions of transaction amount are different for non-fraud transactions and fraud ones. The fraudulent cases are less likely to have very small or very big amount of money because fraudsters don't want to be too noticable. We should focus on the small-medium amount transactions to detect fraud activities.
  • merchantCategoryCode (online_retail, rideshare, subscriptions, online gifts): Whether the transaction happens with one of the 4 merchant categories here can be relevant to decide whether the transaaction is a fraud.

Also, one thing again my intuition is that, I thought the feature matchCVV would be an important feature, but it turns out not. Looks like it is common that people have fat fingers:)

Some Thoughts / Next Steps¶

If I have more time, here are a few items I think would be worthwhile looking into:

  • Data:

    • Imbalance: The data is imbalanced and some model evaluation metrics do not look good. We should try to find more fraudulent samples in order to build a better model.
    • Data Dictionary: The data dictionary is needed here, especially for understanding the pos code.
    • Missing Values: We should work with the DE team to understand the reasons for missing values. Is it originally missing in the database or do the missing records have some special meanings?
    • New Data Sources: It would be great if we have more features available (creditscore, customer tenure, age, income, and etc.,)
    • Reserval Transactions Mismatch: There are 2,547 reversal transactions that I am not able to match with a normal purchase transactions. Probably need to check with DE team as well.

  • Feature Engineering:

    • creditlimit: I notice this field only has limited unique values. We can probably try to treat it as categorical variables instead of numerical to see if anything specifc would jump out.
    • merchantName: I converted it a new feature newMerchant. I am thinking we could also apply some regular expression replacement and string distance calculation to reduce the dimensionality of the variable and create another new feature.
    • More feature engineering can be done here, but we also need be careful for the data leakage issue. (For example, I originally planned to add a new feature to show the total number of fraud transactions occured for that each customer, but then I was worried that it would lead to data leakage as it would be an aggregation across the entire table. We could probably change it to the total number of fraud transactions only up to the current transaction.
  • SMOTE
    • Currently, I am using SMOTE() function to oversampling the data and get 50:50 balance. We can also try other methods to keep the as many original tastes of the data as we can (e.g. We can combine the SMOTE with RandomUnderSampler.)
    • Reference: SMOTE for Imbalanced Classification with Python
  • Modeling:
    • Algorithms: We could try a few more other advanced models and then compare performance. (such as LightGBM and Random Forest)
    • Evaluation metrics: I think we should be focusing on the precision and recall, but it needs to be discussed that which one should be our priority. For example, if the cost of missing a fraud highly outweighs the cost of canceling a bunch of legit customer transactions, i.e. false positives, then perhaps we can choose a weight that gives us a higher recall rate. Or maybe catching 80% of fraud is good enough for your business if you can minimize also minimize the "user friction" or credit card disruptions by keeping our precision high. We could also adjust the weight for f1 score to show the priority.
    • Validation Set: Now we only have training and test set in the model. We can add in the validation set and keep the test set completely out of the model building process.
    • Over-fitting: Although evaluation metrics do not look too bad, the model still suffers from over-fitting issue. We could try to solve this by introducing more samples, further tuning the hyper-parameters, or dropping some irrelevant features.
